# Unit 3a: Basic Objects, Operators, and String Class

## Basic Objects (Structs)

Structs in C++ are a way to group heterogeneous data together in a single unit. They are defined using the `struct` keyword followed by the name of the struct and a list of its members enclosed in curly braces `{}`.

```cpp
struct Point {
    int x;
    int y;
};
```

## Assignment of Objects

Objects of a struct can be assigned using the assignment operator `=`. This performs a member-wise copy of the data.

```cpp
Point p1 = {1, 2};
Point p2 = p1; // p2.x is 1, p2.y is 2
```

## . and -> Operators

The `.` operator is used to access members of an object directly. The `->` operator is used to access members of an object pointed to by a pointer.

```cpp
Point p = {1, 2};
Point* ptr = &p;

int x = p.x; // Accessing member x using . operator
int y = ptr->y; // Accessing member y using -> operator
```

## Use of `getline()`

`getline()` is used to read a string from an input stream, including whitespace, up to a delimiter (default is `\n`).

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    std::string line;
    std::getline(std::cin, line); // Read a line from standard input
    return 0;
}
```

## Checking an Input Stream for Failure

You can check if an input stream has failed using the `fail()` member function or by casting the stream to a boolean context.

```cpp
std::cin >> x;
if (std::cin.fail()) {
    // Handle failure
}
```

## Using C++ String Class

The `std::string` class is a powerful tool for handling strings in C++. It provides various operations like concatenation, comparison, and substring extraction.

```cpp
std::string str = "Hello, World!";
std::string sub = str.substr(0, 5); // sub is "Hello"
```

# Unit 3b: Defining Your Own Classes

## Defining Your Own Classes

Classes in C++ are user-defined types that can contain data members and member functions. They are defined using the `class` keyword.

```cpp
class MyClass {
public:
    int myVar;
    void myFunction() {
        // Do something
    }
};
```

## public vs. private

`public` members are accessible from outside the class. `private` members are accessible only from within the class or friend functions.

```cpp
class MyClass {
private:
    int privateVar; // Accessible only from within MyClass
public:
    int publicVar; // Accessible from anywhere
};
```

## Constructors and Destructors and When They Execute

Constructors are called when a new object of the class is created. Destructors are called when an object is destroyed (goes out of scope or is deleted).

```cpp
class MyClass {
public:
    MyClass() { // Constructor
        // Initialize object
    }
    ~MyClass() { // Destructor
        // Clean up
    }
};
```

## Defining Member Functions

Member functions can be defined inside or outside the class body. If defined outside, they need to be declared inside the class and defined using the scope resolution operator `::`.

```cpp
class MyClass {
public:
    void myFunction(); // Declaration
};

void MyClass::myFunction() { // Definition
    // Implementation
}
```

## Splitting Your Class into Files

Classes can be split into header files (`.h` or `.hpp`) containing declarations and source files (`.cpp`) containing definitions.

- `MyClass.h`: Contains class declaration.
- `MyClass.cpp`: Contains member function definitions.

# Unit 4a: Linked Lists

## Linked Lists

A linked list is a linear data structure where each element is a separate object (node) connected by pointers.

```cpp
struct ListNode {
    int data;
    ListNode* next;
};
```

## Implementing Basic Operations

- `push`: Add an element to the front or back of the list.
- `pop`: Remove an element from the front or back of the list.

```cpp
void push_front(ListNode** head, int data) {
    ListNode* newNode = new ListNode{data, *head};
    *head = newNode;
}

void pop_front(ListNode** head) {
    ListNode* temp = *head;
    *head = (*head)->next;
    delete temp;
}
```

## Efficiency of Various Operations

- With or without a tail pointer, `push_back` can be O(1) if the tail is maintained.
- `pop_back` is O(n) without a tail pointer, as you need to find the second-to-last node.

## Pros and Cons Compared to Arrays

- Pros: Dynamic size, efficient insertion/deletion at the beginning or end.
- Cons: Slower random access, more memory overhead.

# Unit 4b: `vector<T>` and `deque<T>` Basic Operations

## `vector<T>` and `deque<T>` Basic Operations

`vector<T>` and `deque<T>` are part of the C++ Standard Template Library (STL). `vector<T>` is a dynamic array, while `deque<T>` is a double-ended queue.

```cpp
#include <vector>
#include <deque>

std::vector<int> vec = {1, 2, 3};
std::deque<int> deq = {4, 5, 6};

vec.push_back(4); // Add element at the end
deq.push_front(3); // Add element at the front
```

## Efficiency of Their Operations

- `vector<T>`: Fast random access, slow insertion/deletion at the beginning or middle.
- `deque<T>`: Fast insertion/deletion at both ends, slower in the middle.

# Unit 4c: Doubly Linked Lists and `deque<T>` Class

## Doubly Linked Lists

A doubly linked list is a linked list where each node has two pointers: one to the next node and one to the previous node.

```cpp
struct DoublyListNode {
    int data;
    DoublyListNode* prev;
    DoublyListNode* next;
};
```

## `deque<T>` Class

`deque<T>` is implemented using a form of a doubly linked list of fixed-size arrays. It provides fast insertion/deletion at both ends.

## Implementing Basic Operations

Implementations for doubly linked lists involve managing both `next` and `prev` pointers.

```cpp
void push_back(DoublyListNode** head, DoublyListNode** tail, int data) {
    // ...
}

void pop_back(DoublyListNode** head, DoublyListNode** tail) {
    // ...
}
```

## Efficiency of Various Operations

- Doubly linked lists: O(1) for insertion/deletion at both ends.
- `deque<T>`: O(1) for insertion/deletion at both ends, amortized over many operations.

# Unit 4d: Multidimensional Arrays

## Memory Layout of a Multidimensional Array

Multidimensional arrays are stored in row-major order in memory.

## Passing Multidimensional Arrays to Functions

When passing multidimensional arrays to functions, you need to specify the size of all dimensions except the first.

```cpp
void printArray(int arr[][3], int rows) {
    for (int i = 0; i < rows; ++i) {
        for (int j = 0; j < 3; ++j) {
            std::cout << arr[i][j] << ' ';
        }
        std::cout << std::endl;
    }
}

int main() {
    int arr[2][3] = {{1, 2, 3}, {4, 5, 6}};
    printArray(arr, 2);
    return 0;
}
```

# Unit 4e: Passing by Reference

## Syntax and Use

Passing by reference allows you to pass variables to functions as references, allowing the function to directly access the original variable.

```cpp
void increment(int& x) {
    x++;
}

int main() {
    int a = 1;
    increment(a); // a is now 2
    return 0;
}
```

## Advantages of Passing by Reference

- More efficient for large objects as it avoids copying.
- Allows the function to modify the original variable.

## Const References

`const` references are used when you want to ensure the function does not modify the passed object.

```cpp
void print(const std::string& str) {
    std::cout << str << std::endl;
}
```

# Unit 4f: File I/O

## Checking for Failure When Opening a File

When opening a file, always check if the operation was successful.

```cpp
std::ifstream inputFile("input.txt");
if (!inputFile) {
    // Handle error
}
```

## Using C++ `ifstream` and `ofstream` Classes for File I/O

`ifstream` is used for reading files, while `ofstream` is used for writing files.

```cpp
#include <fstream>

int main() {
    std::ifstream inputFile("input.txt");
    std::ofstream outputFile("output.txt");

    std::string line;
    while (std::getline(inputFile, line)) {
        outputFile << line << std::endl;
    }

    inputFile.close();
    outputFile.close();
    return 0;
}
```

## Checking for Failure When Attempting to Receive Input

Check the stream state after attempting to read.

```cpp
int value;
if (!(inputFile >> value)) {
    // Handle error
}
```

This guide provides a comprehensive overview of the specified C++ concepts, including basic objects, classes, linked lists, vectors, deques, multidimensional arrays, passing by reference, and file I/O.

